        <h1>NYT faults cats for aiding misinformation</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-02T04:27:29+00:00">2 Dec, 2021 04:27</time>
        <time class="op-modified" dateTime="2021-12-02T06:52:47+00:00">2 Dec, 2021 06:52</time>    </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>The New York Times has identified another culprit in its war on ‚Äúmisinformation,‚Äù claiming that cute animals featured in viral content help to spread right-wing propaganda and coronavirus conspiracies.</strong></p>
    <p>In the article, titled &lsquo;Those Cute Cats Online? They Help Spread Misinformation&rsquo;, New York Times technology reporter Davey Alba&nbsp;<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/12/01/technology/misinformation-cute-cats-online.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">claimed</a>&nbsp;<em>&ldquo;videos and GIFs of cute animals &mdash; usually cats&rdquo;</em> were being used by <em>&ldquo;people and organizations peddling false information online.&rdquo;</em></p>
            <figure class="op-interactive">
            <iframe>
                <blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">Videos and GIFs of cute animals ‚Äî usually cats ‚Äî have gone viral for almost as long as the internet has been around. <br><br>But now this trick for building audiences is being used by people and organizations peddling misinformation, researchers say. <a href="https://t.co/xw7MqEaSz1">https://t.co/xw7MqEaSz1</a></p>&mdash; The New York Times (@nytimes) <a href="https://twitter.com/nytimes/status/1466051463206080517?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">December 1, 2021</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
            </iframe>
        </figure>
    

<p>Alba listed the US conservative publication Western Journal and the anti-Beijing newspaper The Epoch Times as just a few examples of outlets supposedly using animal content to redirect unsuspecting viewers towards <em>&ldquo;misinformation.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p>According to the article, The Epoch Times has featured cute animals in 12,062 social media posts across 103 Facebook pages, with the posts containing links towards the newspaper&rsquo;s more political content.</p>
<p>The report received mixed reaction on social media, with critics <a href="https://twitter.com/Cowboysilhouet1/status/1466195746009628673" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">calling</a> its claims <em>&ldquo;preposterous&rdquo;</em> and an overreaction.</p>
            <figure class="op-interactive">
            <iframe>
                <blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-cards="hidden"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">Blaming cats for misinformation! Boycott the nytimes! üôÄüòπ <a href="https://t.co/PQOv0nOuEN">https://t.co/PQOv0nOuEN</a></p>&mdash; bonnie (@bonnie_olivia) <a href="https://twitter.com/bonnie_olivia/status/1466119584679878657?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">December 1, 2021</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
            </iframe>
        </figure>
    
            <figure class="op-interactive">
            <iframe>
                <blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-cards="hidden"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">NOW WE CAN&#39;T EVEN HAVE CAT VIDEOS! <a href="https://t.co/i0uHETcPwV">https://t.co/i0uHETcPwV</a></p>&mdash; Erica SchultzüíÄüíê (@EricaSchultz42) <a href="https://twitter.com/EricaSchultz42/status/1466051837581312001?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">December 1, 2021</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
            </iframe>
        </figure>
    

<p><em>&ldquo;They seem to think it&rsquo;s some sinister conspiracy when in reality it&rsquo;s just people with broad interests who like nice things,&rdquo;</em> one person <a href="https://twitter.com/GraduatedBen/status/1466094618257285127" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">reacted</a>, while another <a href="https://twitter.com/KConnerWriter/status/1466079524961935361" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">accused</a> the newspaper of trying to make people <em>&ldquo;feel guilty for enjoying a cute cat pic.&rdquo;</em></p>

