<body>
<article>
    <header>
                    
<figure>
    <img src="https://cdni.rt.com/files/2021.12/article/61a843352030270a9a356e73.JPG">
    <figcaption>FILE PHOTO: US Army soldiers board a transport plane at Camp Lemonnier, Djibouti, January 5, 2020. / <span class="copyright">Reuters / Senior Airman Daniel Hernandez / US Air Force handout</span></figcaption></figure>
        
        <h1>1,000+ US troops to deploy for Africa</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-02T03:55:56+00:00">2 Dec, 2021 03:55</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>More than 1,000 American National Guard troops will soon be shipped to Eastern Africa for a counter-terrorism mission, intended to shore up US bases dotting the region amid a series of ongoing combat and training operations.</strong></p>
    <p>The military announced the upcoming deployment in a <a href="https://www.nationalguard.mil/News/Article/2855047/virginia-guard-task-force-begins-federal-active-duty-for-africa-mission/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">statement</a> earlier this week, saying that more than 1,000 soldiers from the Kentucky and Virginia National Guards are being prepped for a mission in Africa, the largest <em>&ldquo;single-unit mobilization&rdquo;</em> for the VNG since World War 2.</p>
<p>Dubbed &lsquo;Task Force Red Dragon,&rsquo; the troops will take part in the Pentagon&rsquo;s multi-national counter-terrorism operation in the Horn of Africa, and are <em>&ldquo;trained and equipped to accomplish a wide range of missions throughout the US Africa Command area of responsibility,&rdquo;</em> the Guard said.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em><strong>[Their] primary objective is to provide security for the forward operating bases maintained by the Department of Defense to build partnerships with host nations and improve safety and stability in the region.</strong></em></p>
</blockquote>
            <figure class="op-interactive">
            <iframe>
                <blockquote class="twitter-tweet"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">1,000+ <a href="https://twitter.com/kentuckyguard?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">@kentuckyguard</a> and <a href="https://twitter.com/VaNationalGuard?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">@VaNationalGuard</a> Soldiers are mobilizing as Task Force Red Dragon to provide security in support of <a href="https://twitter.com/CJTFHOA?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">@CJTFHOA</a> in the largest Virginia National Guard single-unit mobilization since World War II. <a href="https://t.co/qIIXceW2f4">https://t.co/qIIXceW2f4</a></p>&mdash; National Guard (@USNationalGuard) <a href="https://twitter.com/USNationalGuard/status/1465342297814585352?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw">November 29, 2021</a></blockquote> <script async src="https://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
            </iframe>
        </figure>
    

<p>The soldiers are expected to be sent to the continent sometime in early 2022, according to a Guard source <a href="https://www.military.com/daily-news/2021/11/29/1000-national-guard-soldiers-deploy-africa-mid-east-wars-wind-down.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">cited</a> by Military.com. While the spokesperson did not specify their destination, the US joint counter-terrorism mission in Eastern Africa is based out of Djibouti&rsquo;s Camp Lemonnier, where some 3,400 American personnel are currently stationed. It is unclear if the Guard soldiers will mark an increase in the overall troop level, or replace others already deployed.</p>
<p>The creation of the new task force comes despite vows from the Joe Biden administration to wind down the sprawling War on Terror launched in the wake of the 9/11 attacks, which has seen US military operations in more than a dozen countries. Though Biden made good on his predecessor&rsquo;s plans to withdraw troops from Afghanistan earlier this year, extensive anti-terror operations have continued across the Middle East and Africa. In a <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2021/06/08/letter-to-the-speaker-of-the-house-and-president-pro-tempore-of-the-senate-regarding-the-war-powers-report/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">letter</a> sent to Congress over the summer, the administration outlined its global military footprint, acknowledging ongoing airstrikes on various militant groups in East Africa and train-and-advise missions with local security forces elsewhere on the continent.&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong><a href="https://www.rt.com/usa/540839-pentagon-iranian-drones-threat/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">READ MORE: Pentagon chief promises Arab allies it will counter Iran</a></strong></p>

    <figure class="op-tracker">
