        <h1>Doctor who oversaw Epstein autopsy quits</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T18:52:28+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 18:52</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>New York City‚Äôs chief medical examiner Dr. Barbara Sampson, who oversaw the autopsy of sex offender Jeffrey Epstein after his reported suicide, has resigned for a job in the private sector after nine years in office.</strong></p>
    <p>Sampson announced her impending resignation in an interview with ABC News on Monday, as opening arguments began in the trial of Epstein&rsquo;s associate Ghislaine Maxwell. After 23 years with the city&rsquo;s medical examiner office, she is taking a job with the Mount Sinai Health System.</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/usa/541899-ghislaine-victim-grooming-jane-epstein/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p><em>&ldquo;I was clearly a role model for so many women who are interested in careers in medicine, in science, and in government. I found that now looking back extremely rewarding,&rdquo;</em> she told the outlet.</p>
<p>The first woman to serve as New York City&rsquo;s ME, Sampson oversaw multiple high-profile autopsies. In August 2014, her office ruled that Eric Garner &ndash; a black man who died during an attempted arrest in Staten Island &ndash; died of homicide caused by <em>&ldquo;compression of neck (choke hold), compression of chest, and prone positioning during physical restraint by police.&rdquo;&nbsp;</em></p>
<p>When the police union pointed out that the hyoid bone in Garner&rsquo;s throat hadn&rsquo;t been fractured, Sampson responded it was <em>&ldquo;false&rdquo;</em> that this would have necessarily happened due to a chokehold.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The officer involved was eventually fired, but was not criminally charged. Garner&rsquo;s family received a $5.9 million settlement from the city.</p>
<p>Five years later, in 2019, Sampson would rule Epstein&rsquo;s death in the Manhattan jail to be suicide. The disgraced financier had been awaiting trial on more sex trafficking charges. He allegedly used a sheet in his cell to hang himself. A Justice Department investigation found that the guards did not do any of their rounds that night, while video cameras at the facility malfunctioned.</p>
<p>The autopsy revealed Epstein&rsquo;s hyoid bone had been broken, which is possible in cases of suicide by hanging, but also happens in cases of strangulation.&nbsp;</p>
