    <meta property="fb:op-recirculation-ads" content="placement_id=131217400945872_131237100943902">
</head>
<body>
<article>
    <header>
                    
<figure>
    <img src="https://cdni.rt.com/files/2021.12/article/61a79f5c85f5400bc72a1118.jpg">
    <figcaption>Michelle Obama ¬© Kamil Krzaczynski / AFP</figcaption></figure>
        
        <h1>Can Michelle Obama lead the Democrats to victory in 2024?</h1>

        <address><a>Robert Bridge</a></address>        <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T17:38:51+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 17:38</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>At a time when people are asking how long Joe Biden can survive as president, who‚Äôs best qualified to take on the Republicans in 2024? With VP Kamala Harris‚Äô poll numbers in the basement, Michelle Obama could be one to watch.</strong></p>
    <p>Earlier this week, Business Insider<a href="https://www.businessinsider.com/biden-2022-midterms-republican-agenda-investigation-oversight-impeachment-2021-11?r=US&amp;IR=T" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> proclaimed</a>, with all the liberal indignation it could muster, that <em>&ldquo;Republicans can&rsquo;t wait to make Joe Biden's life miserable&rdquo;</em> in the event the GOP dominates in next year&rsquo;s midterms.&nbsp;</p>
<p>What the article glaringly failed to understand, however, is that Joe Biden needs no help making his life miserable. From failing to protect the southern border amid a pandemic, to severely<a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-57422456" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> curtailing</a> America&rsquo;s energy independence, to leaving behind hundreds of US civilians in Afghanistan amid the worst-conceived military withdrawal in recent memory, Joe Biden is Joe Biden&rsquo;s worst enemy.</p>
<p>Never before has an American president witnessed such a dramatic turn of political fortune. Elected into office at the ripe old age of 78, with the highest number of votes in a presidential election, political pundits are already debating whether the 46th POTUS is coming or going.</p>
<p>Last week, the White House<a href="https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/582717-biden-intends-to-run-for-re-election-in-2024-psaki-says" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> signaled</a> that wobbly Biden would seek reelection in 2024 despite some understandable &ldquo;Democratic fears.&rdquo; This week, the political winds have already started to shift, with analysts<a href="https://www.express.co.uk/news/world/1528862/Biden-2024-Democratic-Party-popularity-drop-Kamala-Harris-US-latest-VN" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> saying</a> Democrats have &ldquo;given up&rdquo; on the possibility of Biden crawling back from extremely<a href="https://edition.cnn.com/2021/11/18/politics/biden-approval-rating-low/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> low poll numbers</a>.</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/op-ed/540125-democrats-kamala-harris-biden/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>At this point in the game, the non-delusional Democrats in the party (albeit a minority) have long come around to the realization that neither Biden nor his vice president, Kamala Harris, have the slightest chance of successfully representing the Democratic ticket in 2024. Any speculation to the contrary is merely covering fire.</p>
<p>Biden will be 82 years old in 2024, and his handlers already keep him on a tight leash, ready at a moment&rsquo;s notice to call a lid on press conferences before old silver tongue has a chance to utter some impropriety.</p>
<p>Kamala Harris, who last month<a href="https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2021/11/07/biden-approval-falls-38-midterms-loom-usa-today-suffolk-poll/6320098001/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> received</a> a 28% approval rating, is about as far from presidential material as Pluto is from the Sun. Her speeches, which drone exquisitely into ethereal<a href="https://twitter.com/ShuForCongress/status/1465177955894767627" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> nothingness</a>, reveal not only a conspicuous lack of charm and personality, but the depth of her intelligence, which would struggle to free itself from the shallow end of the kiddie pool.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The Democrats will not support this woman&rsquo;s presidential bid, exactly as they<a href="https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/us/2020_democratic_presidential_nomination-6730.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> did not</a> in 2019, and the only reason she is now being considered as a possible candidate in 2024 is to save face; not her face, mind you, but that of the party for being so utterly shortsighted to pair her with Biden in the first place.</p>
<p>This trail of tears brings us to Michelle Obama, who has been touted as one of the last hopes to save the Democratic Party from its own excesses. At first glance, the mere thought of the former First Lady going head to head against the likes of Donald Trump, or any other Republican candidate, sounds like sheer madness. Moreover, it shows how shallow the Democratic bench is as far as raw political talent is concerned. Yet opting for Michelle Obama as the Democratic presidential contender in 2024 is not as half-baked an idea as that of Kamala Harris making a run.</p>
<p>Much like Trump, Michelle Obama has charisma and charm &ndash; boatloads more than Harris &ndash; and is hugely popular among Democratic voters (despite the fact that a recent public opinion poll somehow actually put Harris<a href="https://thehill.com/hilltv/what-americas-thinking/583018-poll-harris-michelle-obama-lead-for-2024-if-biden-doesnt-run" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> ahead</a> of Obama by three percentage points, 13% to 10%, respectively). It&rsquo;s important to remember, after all, that US elections are not determined by intelligence, but by personality and charisma &ndash; the raw essence of any baby kissing, hand-shaking politician.</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/op-ed/539707-texas-secession-ted-cruz/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>Although Obama has little direct experience in the US political jungle, she&rsquo;s been close enough to the beast as a former First Lady to understand how it all comes together. She continues to deny that she has any political ambitions, but in the event she&rsquo;s been secretly honing her debating skills and the art of the savage retort, it is not inconceivable that she could fare very well in any future debates, even against the fearsome Orange Man.</p>
<p>With that said, I believe the Democratic Party is wasting the political talents of one of its most respected members,<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y4fjA0K2EeE&amp;t=226s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> Tulsi Gabbard</a>, the former House representative from Hawaii and soldier who served in the Iraq war in a field medical unit.</p>
<p>Here is an incredibly articulate woman, with the most diverse resume, who has witnessed the horrors of US foreign policy first-hand. Unfortunately, it is exactly Gabbard&rsquo;s professed commitment to rid the US political system of its warmongering ways &ndash; she once<a href="https://twitter.com/TulsiGabbard/status/1185289626409406464" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> called</a> Hillary Clinton <em>&ldquo;the queen of warmongers, embodiment of corruption, and personification of the rot that has sickened the Democratic Party</em>&rdquo; &ndash; that prevents this woman from getting the attention she deserves.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Gabbard &ndash; who ran for president before suspending her election campaign &ndash; was one of seven contenders who earned delegates during the 2019 primary. Yet she was the only one not<a href="https://www.newsweek.com/tulsi-gabbard-only-non-white-dem-candidate-primary-delegates-confirms-she-was-not-invited-dnc-1526776" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> offered</a> a speaking slot at the Democratic National Convention, thereby proving once again the folly of US politics, where the American people have the freedom to vote every four years, but only for the pre-selected field of candidates chosen for them.</p>
<p>Perhaps it is best to wrap this up with remarks from one of the most experienced politicians in the world today, Russian President Vladimir Putin.&nbsp;</p>
<p>On the possibility of Joe Biden running again in 2024, Putin<a href="https://www.rt.com/russia/541789-putin-biden-president-bid-2024/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> said</a>, <em>&ldquo;As for Biden&rsquo;s announcement about his possible re-election, I think he was absolutely correct to do so. Because if election preparations were already beginning in America, the management of the country would suffer significantly.&rdquo;</em></p>
<p>Spoken like a true statesman.</p>

