        <h1>French presidential candidate accused of ‚Äòpiracy‚Äô</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T15:44:53+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 15:44</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>Media outlets, celebrities, and film production companies have expressed outrage over the unauthorized use of their images in a campaign video by far-right presidential candidate Eric Zemmour.</strong></p>
    <p>The 63-year-old announced his bid for the presidency on Tuesday in a video that featured him speaking over footage of women in headscarves and black men engaging in civil disobedience.</p>
<p>The right-wing pundit and author said he wanted to &ldquo;<em>save</em>&rdquo; France from minorities that &ldquo;<em>oppress the majority</em>.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
    <figure class="op-interactive">
        
                    <div class="media__youtube">        <iframe class="media__youtube-frame" width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/k8IGBDK1BH8" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
    </div>            </figure>


<p>Movie production company Gaumot quickly accused him of using its content<strong data-stringify-type="bold">&nbsp;</strong>without permission.</p>
<p>&ldquo;<em>Gaumont was surprised to discover that clips of the films from its catalogue have been included into Eric Zemmour&rsquo;s campaign video without any authorization.&nbsp;Gaumont reserves the right to initiate legal proceedings</em>,&rdquo; read the statement by the company, which owns the rights for Luc Besson&rsquo;s Joan of Arc movie and Henri Verneuil&rsquo;s &lsquo;A Monkey In Winter&rsquo;, both featured in Zemmour&rsquo;s video.</p>
<p>Besson also expressed his fury, telling AFP the images were used &ldquo;<em>in a fraudulent manner</em>&rdquo; and that he &ldquo;<em>shares none of Eric Zemmour&rsquo;s ideas</em>.&rdquo;</p>
<p>In his 10-minute-long video, Zemmour warned of the &ldquo;<em>tragic fate</em>&rdquo; facing the traditional and once-great France, saying it was disappearing due to an influx of migrants and multiculturalism.</p>
<p>France Televisions, the National Audiovisual Institute, and Radio France in a joint statement claimed they never gave Zemmour permission to use their images and that the presidential hopeful should pay for the right to use them &ldquo;<em>like everyone else</em>.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/news/541770-france-zemmour-macron-president/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>France 24 said it would demand the immediate removal of its footage and would be prepared, if necessary, to use legal means.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, the owner of a chateau featured in the campaign video, Casimir de Blacas, labeled the use of images of his &ldquo;<em>family home</em>&rdquo; as &ldquo;<em>piracy, pure and simple</em>&rdquo;.</p>
<p>When approached by AFP, Zemmour&rsquo;s team said they had enjoyed their right to use &ldquo;<em>short quotes</em>.&rdquo;</p>
<p>However, a lawyer for France&rsquo;s copyright watchdog, SCAM, told the agency this was not the case and that brief extracts could not be used for promotional purposes.</p>

