<article>
    <header>
                    
<figure>
    <img src="https://cdni.rt.com/files/2021.12/article/61a78e9c85f54007e31d4751.JPG">
    <figcaption><span class="copyright">REUTERS/Mike Segar</span></figcaption></figure>
        
        <h1>Young Americans see US democracy as failed ‚Äì poll</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T15:26:27+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 15:26</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>A national survey of 18-to 29-year-old Americans shows more than half believe US democracy has either ‚Äúfailed‚Äù or is ‚Äúin trouble,‚Äù and a significant portion also sees the potential for civil war.</strong></p>
    <p>Of the 52% polled who said they&rsquo;ve lost or are losing faith in America&rsquo;s democratic system, 39% described the country as a <em>&ldquo;democracy in trouble.&rdquo;</em> Another 13% of respondents called it a <em>&ldquo;failed democracy,&rdquo;</em> according to research released on Wednesday by the Institute of Politics at Harvard Kennedy School.</p>
<p>Of the more than 2,100 young Americans surveyed for the poll, only 7% said they believe the US is a <em>&ldquo;healthy democracy,&rdquo;</em> while another 27% consider it a <em>&ldquo;somewhat functioning democracy.&rdquo;</em></p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/usa/541821-americans-choose-enemy-poll/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p>Unsurprisingly, those who identified as Republicans were the most concerned about the state of the US under the leadership of Joe Biden &ndash; a Democrat with sinking poll numbers as he attempts to address numerous crises, including the Covid-19 pandemic, supply chain issues, and record inflation.</p>
<p>Biden&rsquo;s approval numbers among young voters in the Harvard poll represented declines similar to other recent surveys. Only 46% of respondents to this survey said they approved of the president&rsquo;s job performance &ndash; a 13% drop from a similar poll that was taken by the group in April.&nbsp;</p>
<p>While Democrats expressed the most faith in the country, 45% said the US is either a democracy in trouble or one too far gone. Only 11% of those self-identified Democrats called the US a <em>&ldquo;healthy democracy&rdquo;</em> in the poll. Meanwhile, over half of Republicans and independents agreed that the US has failed or is in trouble, with 70% saying they held a negative view of the state of the country.&nbsp;</p>
<p>In perhaps the polling&rsquo;s most startling findings, 35% of the young Americans surveyed said they saw the potential for a second civil war in their lifetimes, while a quarter of those polled believed they could see a US state secede within their lifetime.&nbsp;</p>

