        <h1>US Navy ponders cutting training flight hours</h1>

                <time class="op-published" datetime="2021-12-01T14:53:51+00:00">1 Dec, 2021 14:53</time>
            </header>

    
    
    <p><strong>Allowing pilots to use simulators more instead of actual flights would be an efficient way to cut expenses during training, a senior US naval commander has said.</strong></p>
    <p>The military is determined to reduce the <em>&ldquo;pretty staggering&rdquo;</em> cost per flight hour to train pilots, Rear Admiral John Meier, the commander of Naval Air Force Atlantic, said at the annual Interservice/Industry Training, Simulation and Education Conference (I/ITSEC) in Orlando, Florida on Tuesday, as quoted by Defense News.</p>
<p><em>&ldquo;One of the areas that I&rsquo;ve got a laser dot on is how can we reduce some of that flying hours and increase more on the simulation side,&rdquo;</em> Meier said.&nbsp;</p>
        
    <ul class="op-related-articles" title="Read more">
        <li><a href="https://www.rt.com/usa/541167-pentagon-ufo-task-creation/"></a></li>
    </ul>


<p><em>&ldquo;The current balance of flights to simulation today is heavily skewed in flights for most aircraft,&rdquo;</em> he continued, adding that replacing some of the flights with training via simulation events in classrooms <em>&ldquo;would be a step in the right direction.&rdquo;</em>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Meier said simulator hours should not make up more than a quarter of total training time. He noted that the training to fly newer aircraft, such as the F-35 Joint Strike fighter and the P-8A Poseidon patrol plane, relies more heavily on simulations. Training to fly older aircraft, such as the F/A-18E-F Super Hornet, which makes up the bulk of the Navy&rsquo;s fighter fleet, requires more live flying hours.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Meier told Defense News that existing technology allows for a shift toward more simulations without sacrificing the quality of training. He added that the change would let pilots focus more on <em>&ldquo;high-end tactics,&rdquo;</em> rather than on basic maneuvers.</p>
<p>The commandant of the US Marine Corps, General David Berger, said at the same event that the armed forces need modeling and simulation software&nbsp;that&nbsp;<em>&ldquo;replicates the adversary, whether it&rsquo;s Russia&nbsp;or<strong data-stringify-type="bold">&nbsp;</strong>Iran&rdquo;</em> or others.&nbsp;<em>&ldquo;We envision our adversary&nbsp;thinking&nbsp;and operating and fighting like we would, which is a big mistake,&rdquo;</em> he said.&nbsp;</p>

